Intelectual Merit


The project focused on studies of linear and nonlinear effects of spin wave propagation in complicated magnetization landscapes (as one presented in the Fig. 1) and their applications for modern non-conventional computing. The main outcomes of the project in terms of intellectual merit were:


(i) Discovery of an inverted excitation geometry for spin waves [Adv. Mater. Interfaces 2022, 2201323]. In order to convert spin waves into electric signals one can use Spin Hall effect (SHE) in a thin Pt layer deposited on the magnetic sample's surface. In this case damping of propagating waves significantly increases due to excitation of eddy currents in Pt. Inverted geometry significantly reduces damping for the propagating surface spin waves by locking eddy current in highly conductive substrate, simultaneously allowing SHE detection;


(ii) Development of advanced 2D wavevector-resolved Brillouin light scattering (BLS) setup, which allowed to study full magnon and phonon spectra in a wide range of wavevectors (for example see Fig. 3) and allowed two following outcomes to be achieved;


(iii) Nonlinear interactions are crucial in science and engineering. Using BLS spectroscopy in thin Yttrium Iron Garnet (YIG) films, we found and identified a set of nonlinear processes resulting in off-resonant spin-wave excitations - virtual magnons [Phys. Rev. Lett.131, 156705 (2023)]. In particular, we discovered a dynamically strong, correlation-enhanced four-wave interactionprocess of the magnon condensate with pairs of parametric magnons having opposite wave vectors andfully correlated phases (see Fig. 4). Such processes could find applications in new information transfer and data processing technologies, including quantum magnonics and coherent quantum optics;


(iv) Based on the obtained knowledge about themagnon Bose-Einstein Condensate and the overpopulated magnon gas surrounding it, we were able to build unified model of BEC in systems with flux equilibrium [Phys. Rev. B 109, 014301 (2024)].The theory agrees qualitatively with experimental data obtained using BLS spectroscopy during parametric pumping of magnons in room-temperature films of YIG. This understanding brings us closer to obtaining continuous magnonic BEC and applying it to unconventional quantum computing with coherent states;


(v) For hundreds of years, seafarers have told stories about enormous waves that appear out of nowhere and sink ships, but the physics of these rogue waves has only recently begun to be understood. Rogue waves are localized in time and space with amplitudes much larger than surrounding waves.Since the first measurement of an ocean rogue wave in 1995, the physics of rogue waves has been investigated in water and other systems including light and sound. Water rogue waves were synthesized with a time-reversal process, involving recording a localized pulse and re-emitting the time-reversed recorded waveforms, which interfere and refocus into a rogue wave. In frame of this project we were able to observe magnetic rogue waves and study theoir properties inin an out-of-plane-magnetized macroscopic thin YIG film (see Fig. 5.). This experimental achievement brings us one step closer to arbitrary manipulation of huge amplitude spin waves in space and time, which is very demanded for computing applications.


Broader Impacts


During the corse of the project four students (three graduate and one undergraduate) received training in microwave and optical spectroscopy and micromagnetic simulations and took an active part in constructing experimental setups and performing measurements. Everyone working on the project presented their work at scientific conferences and participated in public outreach eventslike annual Cool Science Festival at UCCS. In order to engage broader public and educate them about the magnetic structures, we have created interactive mechanical models of artificial spin ice (ASI) lattices (see Fig. 6). These models were successfully used at science festivals as well as was given to our local Space Foundation's museum exibit. Besides of being good educational model, this device aslo exibits rich nonlinear physics.While at completely different spatial and temporal scales, the observed driven mechanical dynamics appeared to be very similar to that observed at the nanoscale when ASIs are driven into a nonlinear regime. Our macroscopic ASI can be considered as a testbed for nonlinear phenomena at a scale appropriate for dissemination to the general public.					Last Modified: 04/29/2024

